\title{conindex: Rank-Dependent Inequality (Concentration) Indices}
\description{
An R translation of the Stata command \code{conindex} (O'Donnell, O'Neill, Van
Ourti & Walsh, 2016). It computes rank-dependent inequality indices used to
measure socioeconomic inequality in a health or economic outcome.
}
\section{Indices}{

All indices are estimated with the "convenient covariance" regression approach
(Kakwani 1980; Jenkins 1988; Kakwani et al. 1997). The main entry point is
\code{\link[=conindex]{conindex()}}; the index is selected by the options, exactly as in Stata:

\tabular{ll}{
Gini                         \tab \code{truezero} (no \code{rankvar}) \cr
Generalized Gini             \tab \verb{truezero, generalized} \cr
Concentration index (CI)     \tab \verb{rankvar, truezero} \cr
Generalized CI               \tab \verb{rankvar, truezero, generalized} \cr
Modified CI                  \tab \verb{rankvar, limits = min} \cr
Wagstaff                     \tab \verb{rankvar, bounded, limits = c(min,max), wagstaff} \cr
Erreygers                    \tab \verb{rankvar, bounded, limits = c(min,max), erreygers} \cr
Extended CI                  \tab \verb{rankvar, truezero, v} \cr
Symmetric CI                 \tab \verb{rankvar, truezero, beta} \cr
}
}

\section{Measurement scales (from the original help file)}{

\describe{
\item{Fixed}{Unique scale, zero = complete absence (e.g. hospital visits).}
\item{Ratio}{Ratios meaningful, zero = complete absence (e.g. life expectancy).}
\item{Cardinal}{Differences meaningful, zero fixed arbitrarily (e.g. a health
utility index) — use \code{limits = min} for the modified index.}
\item{Ordinal}{Only ordering meaningful (e.g. self-assessed health).}
\item{Nominal}{Classification only, no ordering (e.g. type of illness).}
}
}

